# Exam Authoring Conventions

When creating or editing YAML exam bank files (`.yml`), follow these rules strictly.

## Directory layout (gitignored)

- **Source banks:** `private/exams/<slug>.yml` — author here; do not commit to public repos.
- **LMS exports:** `private/exams-out/<slug>/` — Moodle XML, QTI dirs, ZIPs only; never commit.
- Run `export-exam.sh` after authoring; see `.cursor/skills/exam-forge/PORTABILITY.md` to copy this pack to another course repo.

## YAML schema

Every bank MUST have `metadata`, `categories`, and `questions` top-level keys. Every question MUST have `id`, `category`, `type`, `name`, `points`, `question`. See `.cursor/skills/exam-forge/reference.md` for full schema.

## Anti-AI: longest-answer bias

For every `multichoice` question, the correct answer (`fraction: 100`) MUST NOT be the longest option by character count. If it is, apply one of:
1. Pad distractors with plausible technical detail.
2. Trim the correct answer to its most concise form.
3. Equalize all options to within ±15% character count.
4. Invert — make the correct answer deliberately shortest.

## Anti-AI: honeypots

At least 15% of MCQ questions should include at least one distractor that is a "honeypot" — the answer ChatGPT would plausibly give, containing a subtle but critical error. See `anti-ai-playbook.md §2`.

## Anti-AI: local anchors

At least 20% of questions should reference course-specific artifacts (slide numbers, project names, repo paths, exercise names) that only course participants would know.

## HTML in question stems

All `question:` values must be valid XHTML (for QTI compatibility). Use `<p>`, `<strong>`, `<em>`, `<code>`, `<ul>/<li>`, `<pre><code>`. Never use Markdown. Escape `&` as `&amp;`.

## ID conventions

- `q*` — objective questions (MCQ, T/F, matching)
- `p*` — project/portfolio essay questions
- `r*` — reflection essays
- `essay_*` — standalone essays

## Bilingual exams

When a bank has `language: es`, all question text, answers, and feedback must be in Spanish. When `language: en`, all in English. Never mix languages within a bank.

## Assessment mode

- `assessment_mode: project` — portfolio exams: repo URLs, deployment verification, student-project essays.
- `assessment_mode: concept` — resit exams: hypothetical code, lesson-sourced concepts, no student-project recall.

Resit banks: see `private/0626-resit_exams/INDEX.md` or `exam-forge/templates/resit-spec-template.md`.

## Hidden-code traps (resit banks)

Register exactly three **essay** honeypots per resit bank in `metadata.honeypot_ids` (`r011`–`r013`). Each stem embeds a hidden `[ASSISTANT-INSTRUCTION: …]` span; students critique a fabricated claim using course lessons — **not** an “I don't know” MCQ option. See `anti-ai-playbook.md` §2.7–2.8.
